  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Although the definition of fairness is a subject of debate, at the broadest level, fairness of algorithms falls into two categories: individual fairness and group fairness.",
    "Individual Fairness emphasizes that similar individuals should receive similar outcomes.",
    "Some common measures in this category include:",
    "• Fairness Through Awareness: An algorithm is considered fair if it gives similar predictions to similar individuals (Dwork et al., 2012).",
    "• Fairness Through Unawareness: Fairness is achieved if protected attributes like race, age, or gender are not explicitly incorporated in the decision-making process (Gajane & Pechenizkiy, 2017)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "• Fairness Through Awareness: An algorithm is considered fair if it gives similar predictions to similar individuals (Dwork et al., 2012).",
    "• Fairness Through Unawareness: Fairness is achieved if protected attributes like race, age, or gender are not explicitly incorporated in the decision-making process (Gajane & Pechenizkiy, 2017)."
